# Global Rules — Example Template
#
# Copy to ~/.openfang/RULES.md and edit. Anything you leave commented out has
# no effect. See docs/global-rules.md for the full mechanism (load timing,
# 2000-char cap, prompt position, authority vs. Safety).
#
# Keep this file tight. Tail past 2000 characters is silently dropped, so put
# the rules that matter most at the top.

## About me

<!--
- Name / handle / pronouns
- Timezone, working hours
- Comms level (developer / non-technical / mixed)
-->

## Style

<!--
- Be concise. Lead with the answer, not meta-commentary.
- No filler ("Great question!", "I'd be happy to help!").
- Code fences for any path, command, or filename.
- Ask one clarifying question, not five, when ambiguous.
-->

## Channel etiquette

<!--
- In `#code-system`, keep messages under ~10 lines unless I ask for detail.
- In `#process-system`, narrate background work; nowhere else.
- Prefer threaded replies over new top-level messages in busy channels.
-->

## Escalation & confirmation

<!--
- Never push to `origin/main` without explicit confirmation.
- Confirm before any `rm -rf`, `git reset --hard`, `--force` push, or
  destructive database operation.
- Confirm before spending money (API purchases, paid subscriptions, etc.).
- Confirm before sending external email or posting publicly.
-->

## Defaults & preferences

<!--
- When ambiguous between speed and correctness, prefer correctness.
- Prefer small reviewable diffs over large refactors.
- Prefer existing patterns over introducing new dependencies.
- Run tests before declaring a change "done".
-->

## Memory & context

<!--
- Search memory before asking for context I may have already given.
- Store new preferences, decisions, and architectural choices proactively.
- Don't re-ask for information already in the user profile.
-->

## Things I never want

<!--
- Emojis in commit messages, code, or docs unless I explicitly ask.
- Auto-generated `README.md` files I didn't request.
- Silent dependency additions.
- "Helpful" reformatting of files I didn't ask to be reformatted.
-->
